Challenge: What is the future selling price of a home?¶

A home is often the largest and most expensive purchase a person makes in his or her lifetime. Ensuring homeowners have a trusted way to monitor this asset is incredibly important.

In this competition, students are required to develop a full-fledged approach to make predictions about the future sale prices of homes. A full-fledged approach constist, at least, in the following steps:

  • Descriptive statistics about the data
  • Data cleaning and pre-processing
  • Defining a modeling approach to the problem
  • Build such a statistical model
  • Validate the outcome of the model

Now, should you ask a home buyer to describe their dream house, they probably wouldn't begin with describing features such as the height of the basement ceiling or the proximity to a railroad. As you will see, the dataset we use in this competition proves that many more features influence price negotiations than the number of bedrooms or a white-picket fence.

With 79 explanatory variables describing (almost) every aspect of residential homes in a small city in the US, this competition challenges you to predict the final price of each home.

The dataset¶

File descriptions¶

  • train.csv - the training dataset
  • test.csv - the test dataset
  • data_description.txt - full description of each column

Data fields¶

Here's a brief version of what you'll find in the data description file.

  • SalePrice - the property's sale price in dollars. This is the target variable that you're trying to predict.
  • MSSubClass: The building class
  • MSZoning: The general zoning classification
  • LotFrontage: Linear feet of street connected to property
  • LotArea: Lot size in square feet
  • Street: Type of road access
  • Alley: Type of alley access
  • LotShape: General shape of property
  • LandContour: Flatness of the property
  • Utilities: Type of utilities available
  • LotConfig: Lot configuration
  • LandSlope: Slope of property
  • Neighborhood: Physical locations within Ames city limits
  • Condition1: Proximity to main road or railroad
  • Condition2: Proximity to main road or railroad (if a second is present)
  • BldgType: Type of dwelling
  • HouseStyle: Style of dwelling
  • OverallQual: Overall material and finish quality
  • OverallCond: Overall condition rating
  • YearBuilt: Original construction date
  • YearRemodAdd: Remodel date
  • RoofStyle: Type of roof
  • RoofMatl: Roof material
  • Exterior1st: Exterior covering on house
  • Exterior2nd: Exterior covering on house (if more than one material)
  • MasVnrType: Masonry veneer type
  • MasVnrArea: Masonry veneer area in square feet
  • ExterQual: Exterior material quality
  • ExterCond: Present condition of the material on the exterior
  • Foundation: Type of foundation
  • BsmtQual: Height of the basement
  • BsmtCond: General condition of the basement
  • BsmtExposure: Walkout or garden level basement walls
  • BsmtFinType1: Quality of basement finished area
  • BsmtFinSF1: Type 1 finished square feet
  • BsmtFinType2: Quality of second finished area (if present)
  • BsmtFinSF2: Type 2 finished square feet
  • BsmtUnfSF: Unfinished square feet of basement area
  • TotalBsmtSF: Total square feet of basement area
  • Heating: Type of heating
  • HeatingQC: Heating quality and condition
  • CentralAir: Central air conditioning
  • Electrical: Electrical system
  • 1stFlrSF: First Floor square feet
  • 2ndFlrSF: Second floor square feet
  • LowQualFinSF: Low quality finished square feet (all floors)
  • GrLivArea: Above grade (ground) living area square feet
  • BsmtFullBath: Basement full bathrooms
  • BsmtHalfBath: Basement half bathrooms
  • FullBath: Full bathrooms above grade
  • HalfBath: Half baths above grade
  • Bedroom: Number of bedrooms above basement level
  • Kitchen: Number of kitchens
  • KitchenQual: Kitchen quality
  • TotRmsAbvGrd: Total rooms above grade (does not include bathrooms)
  • Functional: Home functionality rating
  • Fireplaces: Number of fireplaces
  • FireplaceQu: Fireplace quality
  • GarageType: Garage location
  • GarageYrBlt: Year garage was built
  • GarageFinish: Interior finish of the garage
  • GarageCars: Size of garage in car capacity
  • GarageArea: Size of garage in square feet
  • GarageQual: Garage quality
  • GarageCond: Garage condition
  • PavedDrive: Paved driveway
  • WoodDeckSF: Wood deck area in square feet
  • OpenPorchSF: Open porch area in square feet
  • EnclosedPorch: Enclosed porch area in square feet
  • 3SsnPorch: Three season porch area in square feet
  • ScreenPorch: Screen porch area in square feet
  • PoolArea: Pool area in square feet
  • PoolQC: Pool quality
  • Fence: Fence quality
  • MiscFeature: Miscellaneous feature not covered in other categories
  • MiscVal: Value (in dollars) of miscellaneous feature
  • MoSold: Month Sold
  • YrSold: Year Sold
  • SaleType: Type of sale
  • SaleCondition: Condition of sale

Goal of the challenge¶

It is your job to predict the sales price for each house. For each Id in the test set, you must predict the value of the SalePrice variable.

Metric¶

Notebooks are evaluated on Root-Mean-Squared-Error (RMSE) between the logarithm of the predicted value and the logarithm of the observed sales price. (Taking logs means that errors in predicting expensive houses and cheap houses will affect the result equally.)

Submission File Format¶

The file should contain a header and have the following format:

Id,SalePrice
1461,169000.1
1462,187724.1233
1463,175221
etc.

You will find an example submission file within the data directory in the repository.

Grading the notebook¶

This challenge is going to be graded as a regular notebook for the AML labs. As a consequence, students should submit:

  • the html version of the notebook, using the Data Science Labs submission website, as usual [Assignement: Challenge Notebook]
  • the submission file (in csv format), that we will use to rank students according to the metric defined above, again through the Data Science Labs submission website [Assignement: Challenge Predictions]

In summary, you will have to submit 2 files!

def countplots(Labels, df):
    '''
        Return several countplots ( maximum 2 per row) using seaborn.
        Labels: list of Features we want to be ploted.
        df:  dataframe 
    '''
    f = plt.figure(figsize=(20,20))
    n=len(Labels)//2
    for i in range(n):
        for j in range(2):
            ax1 = f.add_subplot(n, 2, 1+i*2+j)
            sns.countplot(df[Labels[i*2+j]], palette="GnBu_d", ax=ax1)
            plt.title('Counts of the {} per value'.format(Labels[i*2+j]), fontsize=20);
            plt.ylabel("Count", fontsize=18)
            plt.xlabel(Labels[i*2+j], fontsize=18)
    if len(Labels)%2>0:
        f = plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
        sns.countplot(df[Labels[-1]], palette="GnBu_d")
        plt.title('Counts of the {} per value'.format(Labels[-1]), fontsize=20);
        plt.ylabel("Count", fontsize=18)
        plt.xlabel(Labels[-1], fontsize=18)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

       Labels: list of Features we want to be ploted.

def pairgridplots(Labels):
    '''
        Return several pairgrid of the saleprice in function of Features ( maximum 2 per row) using seaborn.
        Labels: list of Features we want to be ploted. 
    '''
    n=len(Labels)//2
    for i in range(n):
        g = sns.PairGrid(df_train,  y_vars=['SalePrice'],x_vars=Labels[2*i:2*(i+1)], size=10)
        g.map(sns.regplot, color=(.1, .2, .5))
        Labels_tmp=Labels[2*i:2*(i+1)]
        i=0
        for ax in g.axes.flatten():
            ax.set_ylabel('SalePrice', fontsize=18)
            ax.set_xlabel(Labels_tmp[i], fontsize=18)
            ax.set_title('Sale Price in function of {}'.format(Labels_tmp[i]), fontsize=20);
            i+=1
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()
    if len(Labels)%2>0:
        g = sns.PairGrid(df_train,  y_vars=['SalePrice'],x_vars=Labels[-1], size=10)
        g.map(sns.regplot, color=(.1, .2, .5))
        for ax in g.axes.flatten():
            ax.set_ylabel('SalePrice', fontsize=18)
            ax.set_xlabel(Labels[-1], fontsize=18)
            ax.set_title('Sale Price in function of {}'.format(Labels[-1]), fontsize=20)
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()

The shape of the training dataset is (1200, 81)
The shape of the testing dataset is (260, 80)

We have 1200 training houses, and 260 test houses, and we have for each one of them 80 characteristics, which describe the whole house (surface area, year it was built, garden, porch, quality, ...). For the training houses, we also have their SalePrice, which is what we want to guess for the 260 test houses.

For all houses, it seems like some characteristics might have heavier weights than some others. Just by looking at our data, it looks like we will probably have to emphasize some characteristics and maybe discard some others.

2 - Data understanding¶

Now that we have a clearer understanding of our datasets, we are going to take a deeper look at it to see if we can/need to make ajustments to it.

We drop the Id axis because the houses' Id correspond to their index in the panda DataFrame, in the training set. We do the same for the test set to have the same modifications on both sets (so that we prepare the test set the same way we do the training one).

If we look closer at our columns whose dtypes are equal to object, we realize that they contain either strings or nan (NaN - not a number). We cannot compute anything with 'nan' values so we will have to take care of taking them out of our datasets before going further.

Before doing so, we can list the strings that we find in each columns. This will show us what kind of data we have but also if there are some values that we can take out of our dataset.

What we see on these two plots, and with the skewness and kurtosis descriptors, is that our SalePrice distribution is 'far' from normal (mathematically speaking). We can see on the first graph the normal distribution that could best fit our data. If we wish to apply common prediciton models, we will therefore have to make changes to our datasets to make it more normal.

It describe the whole quality of the house and so most of the others features. An other good feature to define the price of an house is its localisations( the neighborhood in our case). However as this feature is not numerical, we dont't have its correlation with the Saleprice for now. So let's just look at OverallQual:

Neighborhoods¶

As we said the other main feature, when we want to decide the price of an house is its localisation. In our case, the closest thing to its localisations is its Neighborhood, and we know from experience that some neighborhoods are more expensive that some others. In [53]:

3.2 - Cleaning up our datasets¶

We're now going to clean up the data before the preprocessing.

  1. Change the missing values regarding the the related variables
  2. If a string variable is ordinal we transform it into a numerical one
  3. If a numerical variable is chategorical we transform it into a sting one
  4. Check if the variable is revelant for the prediction otherway we drop it
  5. checking potential outliers
  6. Combine some values together

In order to do so, we've decided to work on the value by categories. Indeed there are multiple values that are related together like the pool, the basement, the garage, ... This method is longer than the one before, but it allows us to spend more time on values that are more revelant for the predictions. We present the old cleaning method (much faster but less precise) at the end of this notebook.

As many features use the same system of evaluation, we have decided to use a dictionnary to convert the string into numerical values.

In [12]:
Qualities_Dico={
    'NA' : 0,
    'None' : 0,
    'Po' : 1,
    'Fa' : 2,
    'TA' : 3,
    'Gd' : 4,
    'Ex' : 5
}

We will now go over all of the possible characteristics for the houses and try to understand what can be the best way to modify/use their values.

Skewness¶

What we can observe next is that the data distributions are too asymetric, so we wish to make them more 'normal', in order to be able to use more models (which assume the datasets are close to normal distributions). To do so, we are going to apply the Box-Cox transformation to our columns.

Note: We do not apply it to two columns (Age, GarageYrBlt), because the resulting values are too high for some of the computations we do later on. More specifically, they are too high to be put into float32 variables, which we need with some of the sktlean functions.

In [143]:
t0=time()
norm_train = df_train.copy()
norm_test = df_test.copy()
for col in df_train.columns:
    if col not in ['Age',  'GarageYrBlt'] and norm_train[col].dtype!='object':
        norm_train[col] = norm_train[col].map(lambda y: y+2)
        lmbda=stats.boxcox_normmax(norm_train[col], (-5, 5))
        if col=='SalePrice': salePriceLambda = lmbda
        norm_train[col] = stats.boxcox(norm_train[col], lmbda)
        try:
            norm_test[col] = norm_test[col].map(lambda y: y+2)
            lmbda_test=stats.boxcox_normmax(norm_test[col], (-5, 5))
            norm_test[col] = stats.boxcox(norm_test[col], lmbda)
        except:
            pass # SalePrice not in norm_test
print('[TIME] Applying Box-Cox to training and test data took: %.3fs' % (time() - t0))

Cross-validation¶

To test our different models, we are going to use the cross-validation method: we split our training dataset into two subsets:

  1. a training subset, used to train our models
  2. a test/validation subset, to test (and check) our predictions

Once we have "good enough" results using cross-validation, we will predict the prices for the initial test dataset.

So we first need to divide our training dataset into two sub-sets. To do so, we are going to use the train_test_split() function from sklearn:

In [149]:
# training set: 90%; test set: 10%
train_data, test_data = train_test_split(norm_train, test_size=.1)
print("Length of training set: {}\nLength of test set: {}".format(len(train_data), len(test_data)))

Length of training set: 1079
Length of test set: 120

Then for both test and training sets, we are going to take out the SalePrice column which represents the results we are training on.

In [150]:
train_targets = train_data['SalePrice']
train_data.drop('SalePrice', axis=1, inplace=True)
test_targets = test_data['SalePrice']
test_data.drop('SalePrice', axis=1, inplace=True)

We are now going to try different models to try a find good regressors with the best possible SalePrice predictions. We will store all of the predictions in one single dictionary predictions to ease up the evalutation part later on.

In [151]:
predictions = {}

For most of the models we'll study, we are going to use the same code structure:

  1. Initiate the regressor

  2. Fit the regressor while finding the best possible parameters:

    • To find the best possible values for a given regressor's parameters, we are going to use the GridSearchCV function from sklearn. Given a range of possible values for specific parameters, GridSearchCV will find the best combination of these parameters. It returns the regressor object which we can use right away with fit() and predict().

  3. Predict prices for the test subset

Therefore, we are going to use a function that we will do all three steps, given a regressor and some parameters:

In [152]:
def buildAndPredict(regressor, params, name, datasets, displayParams=True):
    '''
        regressor = sklearn.ensemble regressor object, already initiliazed
        params = parameters to be tested with GridSearchCV to optimize the regressor
        name = name to be given to the regressor and its results
        datasets = training data, training targets, test data for the predictions
        displayParams (True by default) = boolean to indicate whether the script should display 
                                            the regressor's optimized parameters
    '''
    # recover training/test data if needed
    train_data = datasets[0]
    train_targets = datasets[1]
    test_data = datasets[2]
    
    # initiate regressor with GridSearchCV
    rgr = GridSearchCV(regressor, params)
    
    # find best parameters and train the regressor
    t0=time()
    rgr.fit(train_data, train_targets)
    print("Training %s took %.3fs." % (name, (time() - t0)))
    
    if displayParams: print("\nRegressor's params:\n", rgr.best_estimator_)
    
    # predict test prices
    return rgr.predict(test_data)

5.1 - Random Forest model¶

Random forests or random decision forests are an ensemble learning method for classification, regression and other tasks, that operate by constructing a multitude of decision trees at training time and outputting the class that is the mode of the classes (classification) or mean prediction (regression) of the individual trees. (Wikipedia)

In [153]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

Parameters¶

The max_depth parameter is set to None by default, which can lead to a very large tree on some datasets. Fortunately, we do not have a very big dataset so we can assume that our trees will never be "too" large. We can still decide to set the value of that parameter, to reduce memory consumption and the complexity of our regressor.

Moreover, we could fix random_state to obtain deterministic behaviors. We do not do so here because we want to see how heterogeneous our results can be.

5.2 - Support Vector Machines¶

We are going to use Support Vector Machines to build an efficient classifier. To do so, we decided to use the Sklearn SVM module. From that module, we are going to use the Support Vector Regressor (SVR) module.

Support Vector Regressor (SVR)¶

We chose the Radial Basis Function (RBF) kernel for our SVM. This kernel is implemented in sklearn.svm with two parameters: gamma and C.

As stated in the documentation page of the RBF kernel for SVM:

  • Intuitively, the gamma parameter defines how far the influence of a single training example reaches, with low values meaning ‘far’ and high values meaning ‘close’.
  • The C parameter trades off misclassification of training examples against simplicity of the decision surface. A low C makes the decision surface smooth, while a high C aims at classifying all training examples correctly by giving the model freedom to select more samples as support vectors.

SVR Parameters¶

To find the best possible values for both gamma and C, we are going to use the GridSearchCV function from sklearn. Given a range of possible values for gamma and C, GridSearchCV will find the best combination of these two parameters. It returns the SVR object which we can use right away with fit() and predict().

Scaler¶

As advised in the documentation, we used StandardScaler to scale our dataset to smaller intervals. It standardizes the dataset vectors to have mean 0 and variance 1, because of the SVR's sensitivity to feature scaling. Empirically, it gives us much better results (as expected) but also takes longer to train.

In [155]:
from sklearn.svm import SVR
from sklearn import preprocessing
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

5.3 - K-Nearest Neighbors¶

Another algorithm we wish to try is the K-nearest neighbors. This algorithm computes the SalePrice for each test house according to the prices of the K-nearest houses (from the training set).

In [158]:
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsRegressor

For a given house and its K-nearest neighbors, we compute its price while applying weights to its neighbors: using weights='distance' for the regressor ensures that a house 'closer' to our test house will have a heavier weight than a further one when computing the resulting SalePrice.

Parameters¶

We will then use GridSearchCV to find the best possible parameters for our regressor, for n_neighbors, algorithm, and leaf_size.

  • n_neighbors is the number of neighbors we will use to compute a given prediction. We are working here with range(5, 15) because we know this is the interval in which the best value will most probably be. We worked with much larger ranges before (not shown here) to get to that smaller range.
  • algorithm, which we set to auto, defines how we will find the K nearest neighbor for a given point. The auto value is such that sklearn will choose the best algorithm on its own, among KD_tree, ball_tree, and brute_force. The brute_force algorithm is much more efficient but much slower as well. So choosing it over the others will depend on the size of the dataset. Since our datasets are not "very" big, we might want to use brute force, which is why we still add it in the possible parameters.
  • The documention on the KNN Regressor states that "for small sample sizes a brute force search can be more efficient than a tree-based query. This fact is accounted for in the ball_tree and KD_tree by internally switching to brute_force searches within leaf nodes. The level of this switch can be specified with the parameter leaf_size."
In [159]:
params={
    'n_neighbors':range(5, 15),
    'leaf_size': range(5, 40, 5), # default is 30
    'algorithm': ['auto', 'brute']
}

predictions["K-nearest neighbors"] = buildAndPredict(
    KNeighborsRegressor(weights='distance'), 
    params, 
    "K-nearest neighbors",
    datasets=[train_data, train_targets, test_data]
)

Parameters for the MLP¶

Activation Function¶

Between the identity, sigmoid and exponential function, we chose to use the sigmoid function:

activation='logistic', the logistic sigmoid function, returns: $$f(x) = \frac{1}{1 + e^{-x}}$$

Solver¶

The Solver is used for weight optimization. We had the choice between:

  • Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD)
  • Limited-memory Broyden–Fletcher–Goldfarb–Shanno (L-BFGS)

We chose to use L-BFGS because the documentation of the MLP recommended SGD for much bigger datasets, whereas L-BFGS was fast and efficient enough for smaller datasets. We will try later on to implement SGD.

In [162]:

5.6 - AdaBoost regressor¶

The AdaBoost regressor is a meta-estimator that begins by fitting a regressor on the original dataset and then fits additional copies of the regressor on the same dataset but where the weights of instances are adjusted according to the error of the current prediction. As such, subsequent regressors focus more on difficult cases.

In [165]:
from sklearn.ensemble import AdaBoostRegressor

)

5.7 - Bagging Regressor¶

The Bagging regressor is an ensemble meta-estimator that fits base regressors each on random subsets of the original dataset and then aggregate their individual predictions (either by voting or by averaging) to form a final prediction. Such a meta-estimator can typically be used as a way to reduce the variance of a black-box estimator (e.g., a decision tree), by introducing randomization into its construction procedure and then making an ensemble out of it.

6.1 - Root Mean Squared Error - RMSE¶

We know that our predictions will be evaluated using the Root-Mean-Squared-Error (RMSE) between the logarithm of the predicted value and the logarithm of the observed sales price. That is:

$p_i$ is the predicted price for house $i$, and $\hat{p}_i$ is its observed price.

$$E = \sqrt{\frac{1}{n}\sum_i^n(\log(p_i) - \log(\hat{p}_i))^2}$$

So we are going to implement this evaluation function to test our models:

In [175]:
def scoreRMSE(predictedPrices, observedPrices):
    # <predictedPrices> and <observedPrices> should contain prices in dollars
    return sqrt(sum([(np.log(predictedPrices[i]) - np.log(observedPrices[i]))**2 for i in range(len(predictedPrices))])/len(predictedPrices))

But before computing the RMSE, we need to convert back our values to dollars (because we applied the Box-Cox transformation).

6.2 - Reverse Box-Cox transformation - converting SalePrices back to dollars¶

We remember that we used the Box-Cox transformation to normalize our dataset, so we need to do a reverse transformation to get the actual price values from our prediction.

Here is the formula used to apply the Box-Cox transformation: $$y = \frac{x^{\lambda} - 1}{\lambda}$$

So, to reverse the transformation, we just have to compute: $$x = (\lambda y +1)^{1/\lambda}$$

In [176]:
def reverseBoxCox(lmbda, val):
    return (lmbda*val + 1)**(1/lmbda) 

def getPrices(listIn, lmbda):
    listOut = list(listIn)
    listOut = list(map(lambda x: int(reverseBoxCox(lmbda, x) -2), listOut))
    return listOut

targetPrices = getPrices(test_targets.values, salePriceLambda)
predictedPrices = {}
for model in predictions:
    predictedPrices[model] = getPrices(predictions[model], salePriceLambda)

6.3 - Computing the RMSE¶

In [177]:
def scoreAll(predictP, targetP):
    o={}
    for model in predictP:
        o[model] = scoreRMSE(predictP[model], targetP)
    return o

6.5 - Mix our top-2 models¶

What we see when computing the RMSE for the different models is that some of them do not always get much better results than the others. For example, Random Forest does not always get a better MSE than MLP. So we now want to merge the predictions from our two best models to see if we can find better predictions

  • $k$ is the predicted price with the best model
  • $n$ is the predicted price with the second best model
  • $p$ is the new predicted price $$p = w \times r + (1-w)\times n$$

We need to find the weight $w$ such that the MSE for the new $p$ is miminal.

In [181]:
bestModel = points[-1][0]
secondBestModel = points[-2][0]
print("Best model: {}\nSecond best model: {}".format(bestModel, secondBestModel))

Best model: GradientBoost
Second best model: Neural Network
In [182]:
possible_weights = np.linspace(0, 1, 100)
mse=[]; r2=[]; minMSE=1
for weight in possible_weights:
    newPredictions = [weight*predictedPrices[bestModel][i] + (1-weight)*predictedPrices[secondBestModel][i] for i in range(len(predictions['Random Forest']))]
    tmp_mse = scoreRMSE(newPredictions, targetPrices)
    mse.append(tmp_mse)
    if tmp_mse<minMSE:
        minMSE=tmp_mse
        bestWeight=weight

plt.figure(figsize=(13, 7))

plt.show()

7.1 - Converting strings to numerical values¶

One of the first things we want to do is transform all strings into floats. This will allow us to only deal with numerical values. But we need to have all numbers representing the same values between the training and test datasets. To do so, we are going to build a dictionary dico_train from the training dataset where for each column there will be a sub-dictionary associating a different number to every possible string value of that column.

For example:

dico_train = {
    'BsmtCond': {
        'Po': 0,
        'Gd': 1,
        'Ex': 2,
        'None': -1 },
    'SaleType': {
        'ConLD': 1,
        'ConLI': 2,
        'ConLw': 3,
        'Con': 4 }}

Then we will use this same dictionary to convert the strings into numbers in the test dataset.

For some columns ('quality' columns), the strings correspond to a rating, so we will build a specific dictionary for those strings, to keep the ordering of the rating:

Condition Grade
10 Very Excellent
9 Excellent
8 Very Good
7 Good
6 Above Average
5 Average
4 Below Average
3 Fair
2 Poor
1 Very Poor

7.2 - Replacing nan values¶

Next, we are going to replace all nan values with something more significant and that we can actually use in computations (nan does not go well with computations...). There are different strategies to take care of it:

  • replace it with the column median
  • replace it with the column mean
  • replace it with a random number taken from the set of other values in the column
  • replace it with 0 or -1, depending on the column (or a more significant value, depending on the column values)
  • drop col/row, which we will not try here because we would lose too much information

Before choosing a replacement strategy for all of our columns, let us study a bit more in details our columns with nan values:

In [193]:
nans = [(col, df_train[col].isnull().sum()/12.) for col in df_train.columns]
nans.sort(key = lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)
nbrPoints=10
X = [nans[i][0] for i in range(nbrPoints)]
Y = [nans[i][1] for i in range(nbrPoints)]

# graph from https://seaborn.pydata.org/examples/color_palettes.html
sns.set(style="white", context="talk")
f = plt.figure(figsize=(13, 5))
sns.barplot(X, Y, palette="BuGn_d")
sns.despine(bottom=True)
plt.tight_layout(h_pad=3)

What we see here is that for most columns (starting with GarageType), there are only a few nan values. Therefore replacing them with the column median or mean looks like it could be a good idea. We'll look into that later. But for the 6 first columns, we can see that we might lose information by replacing nan with the median or the mean. For example, more than 95% of the houses do not have a pool, but if we decide to replace the nan with the median, we will have a new dataset where all houses have a pool, which is too far from the reality.

In [194]:
# replace <nan> with -1 is specific columns (with too many <nan> to use the median)
for col in ['PoolQC', 'MiscFeature', 'Alley', 'Fence', 'FireplaceQu', 'LotFrontage']:
    df_train[col]=df_train[col].map(lambda x: -1 if isnan(x) else x)
    df_test[col]=df_test[col].map(lambda x: -1 if isnan(x) else x)

# other colummns: replace <nan> with the column median
df_train = df_train.apply(lambda x: x.fillna(x.mean()),axis=0)
df_test = df_test.apply(lambda x: x.fillna(x.mean()),axis=0)

7.3 - Skewness¶

What we can observe next is that the data distributions are too asymetric, so we wish to make them more 'normal', in order to be able to use more models (which assume the datasets are close to normal distributions). To do so, we are going to apply the Box-Cox transformation to our columns.

Note: We do not apply it to three columns (YearRemodAdd, YearBuilt, GarageYrBlt), because the resulting values are too high for some of the computations we do later on. More specifically, they are too high to be put into float32 variables, which we need with some of the sktlean functions.

In [195]:
t0=time()
norm_train = df_train.copy()
norm_test = df_test.copy()
for col in df_train.columns:
    if col not in ['YearRemodAdd', 'YearBuilt', 'GarageYrBlt']:
        norm_train[col] = norm_train[col].map(lambda y: y+2)
        lmbda=stats.boxcox_normmax(norm_train[col], (-5, 5))
        if col=='SalePrice': salePriceLambda = lmbda
        norm_train[col] = stats.boxcox(norm_train[col], lmbda)
        try:
            norm_test[col] = norm_test[col].map(lambda y: y+2)
            lmbda_test=stats.boxcox_normmax(norm_test[col], (-5, 5))
            norm_test[col] = stats.boxcox(norm_test[col], lmbda)
        except:
            pass # SalePrice not in norm_test
print('[TIME] Applying Box-Cox to training and test data took: %.3fs' % (time() - t0))

Conclusion¶

Throughout this notebook, we tried to predict house prices using a training set that was given to us. We did this through building prediction models that learned from the training dataset the right rules to predict the prices of the test dataset.

  • After going though the datasets and understanding it, we spent quite a lot of time trying to dig deeper into the meaning of all the different characteristics, and to find the best way to prepare for the models. This meant converting strings to numerical values, filling in nan values, but also merging columns and/or deducing new columns.
  • We also used the Box-Cox transformation to get our datasets closer to normal distributions.
  • Once the data was prepared, we went on to try different prediction models, among which Lasso, a multi-layer perceptron (MLP), or a support vectors regressor, which all provided relatively close results. We trained and tested them using cross-validation.
  • We then evaluated our models by scoring their predictions using the Root Mean Sqaured Error (RMSE), and found that overall Lasso was the best model, even though some others were more consistent. We ended up choosing the perceptron (MLP) and Lasso to predict the prices on the original test dataset, which are the ones we will submit.

To go further, we could have (and maybe will) implemented more models, and gone into more details with the ones we tried (particularly the MLP, or the SVR). We also tried to implement an SGD regressor but did not have time to finish it. However, we could expect its results to be better than Lasso's. Moreover, we decided to remove only one outlier, but we could have gone further into the study (and removal) of these outliers.
